definition.value: a role that is intrinsic to a patient and is associated with an adverse event. No causal effect between this factor and the adverse event is assumed.  Examples include: age, race, organ dysfunction, disease, pregrancy, lactation, gender, and genetics.

label.value: organ dysfunction factor of adverse event

label.value: determination of causal drug adverse event by Naranjo criteria

definition.value: an identification of causal drug adverse event that is based on the Naranjo criteria.

label.value: determination of causal drug adverse event by DIPS

definition.value: an identification of causal drug adverse event that is based on the Drug Interaction Probability Scale (DIPS). The DIPS uses a series of questions relating to the potential drug interaction to estimate a probability score. As a comparison, the Naranjo scale has proved to be useful for assessing the causality of adverse events, particularly for single-drug adverse drug reactions. DIPS involves in two drugs: the drug that is affected (object drug) and the drug that causes the change to the object drug (precipitant drug).
an information content entity that lists one of 10 questions for the Drug Interaction Probability Scale (DIPS).
DIPS question 1: Are there previous credible reports of this interaction in humans?
DIPS question 2: Is the observed interaction consistent with the known interactive properties of precipitant drug?
DIPS question 3: Is the observed interaction consistent with the known interactive properties of object drug?
DIPS question 4: Is the event consistent with the known or reasonable time course of the interaction (onset and/or offset)?

DIPS question 5: Did the interaction remit upon dechallenge of the precipitant drug with no change in the object drug?
(if no dechallenge, use Unknown or NA and skip Question 6)
DIPS question 6: Did the interaction reappear when the precipitant drug was readministered in the presence of continued use of object drug?
DIPS question 7: Are there reasonable alternative causes for the event?
DIPS question 8: Was the object drug detected in the blood or other fluids in concentrations consistent with the proposed interaction?
DIPS question 9: Was the drug interaction confirmed by any objective evidence consistent with the effects on the object drug (other than drug concentrations from question 8)?
DIPS question 10: Was the interaction greater when the precipitant drug dose was increased or less when the precipitant drug dose was decreased?
an AE causality score that is represented as a score of the Drug Interaction Probability Scale (DIPS).
DIPS question 1: Are there previous conclusive reports on this reaction?
DIPS question 2: Did the adverse reaction appear after the suspected drug was administered?
DIPS question 3: Did the adverse reaction improve when the drug was discontinued or a specific antagonist was administered?
DIPS question 4: Did the adverse reaction reappear when the drug was readministered?
DIPS question 5: Are there alternative causes that could on their own have caused the reaction?
DIPS question 6: Did the reaction reappear when a placebo was given?
DIPS question 7: Was the drug detected in the blood (or other fluids) in concentrations known to be toxic?
DIPS question 8: Was the reaction more severe when the dose was increased or less severe when the dose was decreased?
DIPS question 9: Did the patient have a similar reaction to the same or similar drug in any previous exposure?
DIPS question 10: Was the adverse event confirmed by any objective evidence?
a score of the Naranjo adverse drug reaction probability scaling
an adverse event causal association score that represents a probability that an adverse event is caused (induced) by a medical intervention.
a peripheral neuropathy AE which has an outcome of sensory neuropathy that involves damage to nerves of the peripheral nervous system.
a sensory neuropathy AE which has an outcome of distal sensory neuropathy that involves damage to distal sensory nerves of the peripheral nervous system.
a distal sensory neuropathy AE that is chronic.
